07947nam a22012135i 9781614510185DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112011gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)853262022  a97816145101857 a10.1515/97816145101852doi  a(DE-B1597)173798  a(OCoLC)769190335  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP53 .P734 2011 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a418.007100aProcesses and Process-Orientation in Foreign Language Teaching and Learning /ced. by Wai Meng Chan, Kwee Nyet Chin, Masanori Nagami, Titima Suthiwan. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (387 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Second and Foreign Language Education [SSFLE] ,x2192-0982 ;v40 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere can be no products without processes. Though this statement may seem to be no more than an overused generalization, it encapsulates the undoubted importance of processes and process-oriented approaches in language teaching and learning. In foreign language education in recent decades, researchers and practitioners alike are increasingly focusing their attention on: 1) the learner as the active subject of learning and the internal processes that constitute his/her learning leading to the development of communicative competence; 2) teaching approaches, curricula and materials that reflect this view of language learning; and 3) other factors such as the sociocultural context, social interactions and discourse, and individual learner characteristics and differences. The theme of this book reflects this paradigm shift, and the papers included here from the disciplines of foreign language education and second language acquisition provide vital insights into processes in curriculum planning, teaching methodology, teacher education and professional development, language acquisition, language discourse, classroom instruction and interactions, the development of language skills and learning strategies, and language learning motivation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisition. 4aAngewandte Linguistik. 4aFremdsprachendidaktik. 4aFremdsprachenerwerb. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLanguage Acquisition, Language Teaching, Language Education, Applied Linguistics.1 aAbe, Yuko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Wai Meng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Wai Meng, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChang, Shanmao Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheng, Hsiao-fang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin, Kwee Nyet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin, Kwee Nyet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFinch, Andrew Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Shenghui Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIstanto, Johanna W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawaguchi, Yoshikazu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaskar, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Chen-Ying, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittlewood, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagami, Masanori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagami, Masanori, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel